Visual inspection of the maps of the observed diarrhoea and fever prevalence by regions and districts (Fig. 1, Fig. 2
) suggest that regional classification conceal district variations. Table 1
shows that overall, the highest prevalence of both diarrhoea and fever were observed in the Central region, followed by the Southern region. Although the Northern region reported the lowest overall prevalence of both fever and diarrhoea, it had the district with the highest fever incidence of 63 percent (Nkhata Bay), further confirming that regional classifications do mask important district variations.

The result of the nonlinear effect of child's age (Fig. 7
) suggests that there is continuous worsening of the child morbidity rate up to about 8 months of age. Fig. 8
shows the influence of the mother's age on fever to be nonlinear, but with a general tendency to decline with age. The results for the youngest and oldest maternal ages are less reliable as shown by the wide CIs.
